translation_unit_file: ALIGNAS LPAREN VOID LPAREN LPAREN RPAREN COMMA 
##
## Ends in an error in state: 289.
##
## direct_abstract_declarator -> LPAREN direct_abstract_declarator . RPAREN [ RPAREN LPAREN LBRACK COMMA ]
## direct_abstract_declarator -> direct_abstract_declarator . LPAREN in_context(option(parameter_type_list)) RPAREN [ RPAREN LPAREN LBRACK ]
## option(direct_abstract_declarator) -> direct_abstract_declarator . [ LBRACK ]
##
#
# The first LPAREN in this example must be the beginning of an abstract_declarator.
# It leads us into a state where we do not yet know the meaning of the opening parenthesis:
#   direct_abstract_declarator -> LPAREN . pointer RPAREN [ RPAREN LPAREN LBRACK ]
#   direct_abstract_declarator -> LPAREN . direct_abstract_declarator RPAREN [ RPAREN LPAREN LBRACK ]
#   direct_abstract_declarator -> LPAREN . pointer direct_abstract_declarator RPAREN [ RPAREN LPAREN LBRACK ]
#   direct_abstract_declarator -> LPAREN . in_context(option(parameter_type_list)) RPAREN [ RPAREN LPAREN LBRACK ]
# i.e. (a-b-c) this could be the opening parenthesis in a pair of parentheses,
#   or (d) this could be the opening parenthesis in a function type.
# The second LPAREN takes us again into the same state.
# The RPAREN allows us to recognize that we have a function type of no parameters (d).
# Hence, LPAREN RPAREN forms a direct_abstract_declarator.
# At this point, the status of the first LPAREN is still undetermined (regular paren,
# or beginning of a function type?) but that is not a problem for us.
#
# Thanks to our use of inline_abstract_declarator in this production:
#   direct_abstract_declarator:
#   | LPAREN inline_abstract_declarator RPAREN
# we know for sure that we have recognized a direct_abstract_declarator.
#
# (Without this trick, we would know only that we have recognized either an abstract_declarator or
# a direct_abstract_declarator which has spuriously reduced to abstract_declarator. This would
# pose a problem because we would not know for sure what are the permitted continuations.)
#
# Here, thanks to this trick, there are no spurious reductions, so we know for sure
# what the permitted continuations are.
#
# It is difficult to be consistent in the terminology. Here, a closing
# parenthesis would FOLLOW a direct_abstract_declarator, but would also
# COMPLETE a direct_abstract_declarator, since the production is
# direct_abstract_declarator -> LPAREN direct_abstract_declarator . RPAREN
#
translation_unit_file: ALIGNAS LPAREN VOID LPAREN RPAREN XOR_ASSIGN 
##
## Ends in an error in state: 337.
##
## abstract_declarator(type_name) -> direct_abstract_declarator . [ RPAREN ]
## direct_abstract_declarator -> direct_abstract_declarator . LPAREN in_context(option(parameter_type_list)) RPAREN [ RPAREN LPAREN LBRACK ]
## option(direct_abstract_declarator) -> direct_abstract_declarator . [ LBRACK ]
##
#
# This case is simplified by giving a phantom context parameter to abstract_declarator.
# Here, we know we are in the context of a type_name, so RPAREN is allowed next.
# If we were in the context of a parameter_declaration, COMMA would be allowed next.
#
# This case is very similar to the previous example (which is why we share the
# error message). The states are different because here we know that we are at
# the top level (type_name -> direct_abstract_declarator) whereas in the other
# example we are not (direct_abstract_declarator ->
# direct_abstract_declarator).
#
translation_unit_file: ALIGNAS LPAREN VOID LPAREN STAR LPAREN RPAREN XOR_ASSIGN 
##
## Ends in an error in state: 275.
##
## direct_abstract_declarator -> LPAREN pointer direct_abstract_declarator . RPAREN [ RPAREN LPAREN LBRACK COMMA ]
## direct_abstract_declarator -> direct_abstract_declarator . LPAREN in_context(option(parameter_type_list)) RPAREN [ RPAREN LPAREN LBRACK ]
## option(direct_abstract_declarator) -> direct_abstract_declarator . [ LBRACK ]
##
#
# Another very similar case, it seems.

Up to this point, a direct abstract declarator has been recognized.
At this point, one of the following is expected:
  an opening bracket '[',     continuing this direct abstract declarator; or
  an opening parenthesis '(', continuing this direct abstract declarator; or
  a closing parenthesis ')',  following this direct abstract declarator.

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------

translation_unit_file: ALIGNAS LPAREN VOID LPAREN STAR VAR_NAME 
##
## Ends in an error in state: 333.
##
## direct_abstract_declarator -> LPAREN pointer . RPAREN [ RPAREN LPAREN LBRACK ]
## direct_abstract_declarator -> LPAREN pointer . direct_abstract_declarator RPAREN [ RPAREN LPAREN LBRACK ]
##
## WARNING: This example involves spurious reductions.
## This implies that, although the LR(1) items shown above provide an
## accurate view of the past (what has been recognized so far), they
## may provide an INCOMPLETE view of the future (what was expected next).
## In state 155, spurious reduction of production pointer -> STAR option(type_qualifier_list) 
##

# Both productions above stem from the inlining in
# direct_abstract_declarator -> LPAREN inline_abstract_declarator RPAREN.
# We can describe them by saying we expect an optional direct_abstract_declarator,
# followed with a closing parenthesis.

Up to this point, an opening parenthesis '(' and a pointer have been recognized.
If this pointer is complete,
then at this point,
an optional direct abstract declarator is expected,
followed with a closing parenthesis ')'.

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------

translation_unit_file: ALIGNAS LPAREN VOID LPAREN XOR_ASSIGN 
##
## Ends in an error in state: 332.
##
## direct_abstract_declarator -> LPAREN . pointer RPAREN [ RPAREN LPAREN LBRACK ]
## direct_abstract_declarator -> LPAREN . direct_abstract_declarator RPAREN [ RPAREN LPAREN LBRACK ]
## direct_abstract_declarator -> LPAREN . pointer direct_abstract_declarator RPAREN [ RPAREN LPAREN LBRACK ]
## direct_abstract_declarator -> LPAREN . in_context(option(parameter_type_list)) RPAREN [ RPAREN LPAREN LBRACK ]
##

# The first three productions above stem from the inlining in
# direct_abstract_declarator -> LPAREN inline_abstract_declarator RPAREN.
# The fourth one is different.

An opening parenthesis '(' has been recognized.
At this point, one of the following is expected:
  an abstract declarator,
    if this parenthesis is intended as a delimiter; or
  a parameter type list,
    if this parenthesis is intended as the beginning of a function declarator.

